      "content": "For the 200% declining balance method, the annual depreciation is calculated as:\n\nAnnual Depreciation = (Previous Year's Book Value x Depreciation Rate)\n\nThe depreciation rate is 200% / Useful Life, which is 200% / 10 = 20% per year.\n\nIn Year 1, the book value is $85,000, so the annual depreciation is:\n\nAnnual Depreciation = $85,000 x 20% = $17,000\n\nThe book value at the end of Year 1 is $85,000 - $17,000 = $68,000.\n\nIn Year 2, the annual depreciation is:\n\nAnnual Depreciation = $68,000 x 20% = $13,600\n\nThe book value at the end of Year 2 is $68,000 - $13,600 = $54,400.\n\nAs you can see, the asset's value does indeed drop quickly at the start, but it slows down over time. This is because the depreciation rate decreases each year.\n\nTo give you a better idea, here's a breakdown of the asset's value over the 10-year useful life:\n\nYear 1: $85,000 - $17,000",
